ades."}],"references":["59dc9720-ded9-454e-a56f-7a838f8dd257_40731959","ce56cb3e-c53a-4b45-9cdc-49aba447bcd0_556143933","cad68b28-9613-4010-bbdb-3c946c035b06_156749090"],"documents":{"ce56cb3e-c53a-4b45-9cdc-49aba447bcd0_556143933":{"id":"ce56cb3e-c53a-4b45-9cdc-49aba447bcd0_556143933","text":"Saturday, May 20, 2023\n\nCarping point: Life is tough enough for writers, even without the piracy\n\nFile image.\n\nPublished 1h ago\n\nShare\n\nJohannesburg - It is one of the enduring sadnesses in South Africa that few writers can make a living from writing \u2013 either fiction or non-fiction \u2013 unless their books get picked up internationally. South Africa\u2019s best-selling writers in either format can be listed on each hand \u2013 and there are more successful writers of non-fiction than fiction.\n\nThe only difference is the Afrikaans market which has an almost baked in loyalty and support system guaranteeing a sustainable income. Deon Meyer straddles both worlds but then, he\u2019s one of a kind. He\u2019s a colossus in the Afrikaans fiction market, his books are translated into English and sold here and overseas. He\u2019s even made it into film.\n\nMike Nicol is an incredible writer, who has published several series of best-sellers, but he had to start a writer\u2019s academy running master classes, which, in turn, helps produce the next generation of writers, to create a sustainable career out of writing.\n\nThe fact of the matter is that in South Africa, selling 3 000 copies is regarded by publishers as a best-seller. At 20% of the net selling price as your royalty, paid in tranches over 18 months, you\u2019ll be lucky if you make as much as the national minimum wage.\n\nBut, sometimes, writers shoot the lights out. When Jake White\u2019s Springboks won the World Cup in 2007, his ghosted memoir In Black & White had to go into reprint several times before Christmas. The last time local publishers had seen anything like it was when Nelson Mandela\u2019s Long Walk to Freedom \u2013 13 years before.\n\nThe next great moment came when Jacques Pauw published The President\u2019s Keepers in 2017. It helped create a new genre for local publishers. You could fill bookshelves with the books that detail just how this country has plummeted since Long Walk to Freedom was first published, from Killing Kebble to explaining the demise of Eskom when we thought Stage 2 load shedding was an infraction on our human rights.\n\nSometimes, the subjects themselves do the greatest marketing, like when ANC Youth League members were specially bussed into Sandton\u2019s Exclusive Books to disrupt the launch of Pieter-Louis Myburgh\u2019s Gangster State and burn the book.\n\nBut given how hard it is for the writers to take the personal risks they do and get into print, it\u2019s incredibly galling to discover that their work is being pirated as fast as it is being published. It came to a head with viral PDFs of Pauw\u2019s The President\u2019s Keepers. This week, it was the turn of Andre de Ruyter and his memoir of his three years as Eskom CEO.\n\nAs celebrated author Darrel Bristow Bovey noted on Twitter: \u201cIt strikes me that the only times South Africans are so interested in a book that they share stolen pirated copies of it, the book is always about corruption and thievery \u2013 presumably something of which those South Africans disapprove.\u201d\n\nIt is the bitterest, most quintessential South African irony. It has to stop. Delete the WhatsApp if you got it.\n\nBuy the book instead. It\u2019s the right thing to do.\n\nShare\n\nSectionsMy NewsBookmarksNotificationsSubscribe","url":"https://www.iol.co.za/saturday-star/news/carping-point-life-is-tough-enough-for-writers-even-without-the-piracy-2d67a894-f9a3-4618-9069-bd4d3ccc102b"},"cad68b28-9613-4010-bbdb-3c946c035b06_156749090":{"id":"cad68b28-9613-4010-bbdb-3c946c035b06_156749090","text":"Home / Science / Health /\u00a0 Dengue virus has evolved to become more severe, reveals study, urges for vaccine development\nBack\n\nIndia reports thousands of dengue cases every year and many people lose their life due to the virus. A new multi-dimensional study by the team of the Indian Institute of Science (IISc) has revealed some new details about the virus and informed that the dengue virus has evolved over the last six decades. The study has also pointed towards the urgent need of a vaccine for the dengue virus.\n\nThe team of researchers conducted a computational analysis which revealed that the virus has grown exponentially in the past 50 years. The rise in the spread of the cases of the virus is especially noticed around South-East Asian counties.\n\n\"The reported dengue cases in 2018 have increased more than 25-fold (three-year average) since 2002 in India. All four geographical regions, namely\u2013North, East, South, and West-Central India, show periodic spikes in dengue cases as well as deaths over 2\u20134 years. Comparing all published dengue sequences till 2018 from India, we find all four dengue serotypes co-circulating in the country since 2000,\" the researchers said in a study published in the journal PLOS PATHOGENS.\n\nThe Evolution of Dengue Virus:\n\nThe researchers studied the changes in the four serotypes of the dengue virus and observed how they have changed from their ancestral sequence.\n\nThe 408 genetic sequences of Indian dengue strains were examined during the research and the results reveal that the dengue virus has changed in a very complex manner. The strains of the virus are changing its patterns and the strains which were not very prevalent in India earlier, are spreading rapidly.\n\nFor example, the study mentions that until 2012, Dengue 1 and Dengue 3 were the dominant strains in India, but the situation changed in the past few years with Dengue 2 virus spreading rapidly and Dengue 4 also creating a separate space for itself in the region.\n\nThe research reveals that if a person is infected with two strains of the virus at the same time, the symptoms of the dengue virus can be severe. After primary infection from any of the strains of the virus, antibodies provide protection from other strains also for 2-3 years, but after that cross-serotype protection is lost.\n\nThe study finds that the new strains of the virus are very different from their ancestral sequence and there is an urgent need to develop a vaccine against the dengue virus.\n\nCurrently, the Indian Council of Medical Research (ICMR) is conducting phase-3 trials of a vaccine candidate.\n\nRead More: Climate change spurring surge in dengue, chikungunya: WHO\n\n\u00a0\n\n\u00a0\n\nCatch all the Business News, Market News, Breaking News Events and Latest News Updates on Live Mint. Download The Mint News App to get Daily Market Updates.\nMore Less\nRecommended For You\n\u00d7\nGet alerts on WhatsApp\nSet Preferences My Reads Watchlist Feedback Redeem a Gift Card Logout","url":"https://www.livemint.com/science/health/dengue-virus-has-evolved-to-become-more-severe-reveals-study-urges-for-vaccine-development-11682935170774.html"},"59dc9720-ded9-454e-a56f-7a838f8dd257_40731959":{"id":"59dc9720-ded9-454e-a56f-7a838f8dd257_40731959","text":"Advertisement\n\nUpdated February 19th, 2024 at 14:53 IST\n\nThe Best Sci-Fi Directors in Bollywood\n\nHere, we delve into the realm of sci-fi and highlight some of the best directors in Bollywood who have ventured into this fascinating genre.\n\nDigital Desk\nThe Best Sci-Fi Directors in Bollywood | Image:Republic\nAdvertisement\n\nIn the vast and dynamic landscape of Indian cinema, Bollywood has often been celebrated for its ability to traverse genres, captivate audiences, and push the boundaries of storytelling. While it's often associated with romantic dramas and high-energy musicals, the realm of science fiction has also found its place on the silver screen, thanks to the visionary directors who dared to explore the unknown. Here, we delve into the realm of sci-fi and highlight some of the best directors in Bollywood who have ventured into this fascinating genre.\n\n1.\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0Shekhar Kapur: Renowned for his groundbreaking work in films like \"Mr. India\" (1987) and \"Jaane Bhi Do Yaaro\" (1983), Shekhar Kapur is a visionary director whose foray into science fiction with \"Mr. India\" left an indelible mark on Indian cinema. The film, blending elements of fantasy and sci-fi, introduced iconic characters like Mogambo and showcased innovative special effects for its time, earning Kapur acclaim as a pioneer in the genre.\n\nAdvertisement\n\n2.\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0Rakesh Roshan: Rakesh Roshan is a multifaceted filmmaker known for his versatility across genres. While he is celebrated for his work in family dramas and action thrillers, his venture into sci-fi with \u2018\u2018Koi Mil Gaya\u2019\u2019 and the \"Krrish\" franchise has been monumental. Spanning multiple films, the series follows the journey of a superhero with extraordinary abilities, blending elements of science fiction with Indian mythology to create a unique cinematic universe that has captured the imagination of audiences.\n\n3.\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0S. Shankar: With a penchant for grandeur and spectacle, S. Shankar is a director renowned for his ambitious vision and technical prowess. His venture into sci-fi with films like \"Robot\" (2010) and its sequel \"2.0\" (2018) pushed the boundaries of Indian cinema, featuring cutting-edge visual effects and exploring themes of artificial intelligence and the future of technology. Shankar's ability to seamlessly blend high-concept ideas with mass appeal has solidified his position as a trailblazer in Bollywood sci-fi.\n\nAdvertisement\n\n4.\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0Shailender Vyas: \u00a0Known as \u201cThe Christopher Nolan\u201d of India, Shailender Vyas has made significant contributions to the sci-fi genre in Bollywood. His series \"JL50\" marked a significant departure from conventional Bollywood narratives, showcasing Shailender Vyas' willingness to challenge the status quo. His ability to blend genres and explore unconventional themes demonstrates a refreshing perspective within the sci-fi landscape. Vyas' contribution to the genre serves as a reminder of the importance of creative risk-taking in pushing cinematic boundaries.\n\n5.\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0Vipul Amrutlal Shah: Vipul Amrutlal Shah is a director known for his diverse filmography, spanning genres from romantic comedies to action thrillers. His venture into sci-fi with \"Action Replayy\" (2010) offered a quirky twist on time travel, featuring a blend of retro aesthetics and futuristic concepts. While the film received mixed reviews, Shah's willingness to experiment within the sci-fi genre deserves recognition.\n\nAdvertisement\n\n6.\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0Anubhav Sinha: Anubhav Sinha has carved a niche for himself with socially relevant and thought-provoking cinema. While his filmography predominantly includes dramas and thrillers, his sci-fi venture \"Ra.One\" (2011) showcased his ambition to push the boundaries of storytelling. The film, featuring cutting-edge visual effects and exploring themes of virtual reality and gaming, marked a significant milestone in Bollywood's exploration of the sci-fi genre.\n\nIn conclusion, the realm of science fiction in Bollywood continues to evolve, thanks to the creative vision and innovation of directors like Shekhar Kapur, Rakesh Roshan, S. Shankar, Shailender Vyas, Vipul Amrutlal Shah, and Anubhav Sinha. Through their pioneering efforts, they have expanded the horizons of Indian cinema, captivating audiences with tales that transcend time and space, and leaving an indelible mark on the genre for generations to come.\n\nAdvertisement\n\nPublished February 19th, 2024 at 14:53 IST\n\nYour Voice. Now Direct.\n\nSend us your views, we\u2019ll publish them. This section is moderated.\n\nAdvertisement\nAdvertisement","url":"https://www.republicworld.com/initiatives/the-best-sci-fi-directors-in-bollywood/"}}}
